<p>Two boats carrying about 95 irregular migrants capsized off the Libyan coastal city of Al Khums on Thursday, the Libyan Red Crescent said, and at least four people were killed in the incident. The Red Crescent said it rescued 91 migrants and asylum seekers, who included people from Bangladesh, Sudan and Egypt. Officials gave limited detail on what caused the sinkings and which other agencies were involved in the rescue effort.</p><img src='https://kagiproxy.com/img/4OgOofSOad_Rh1r3louce1WDQrdmBNUlQzA00leM10mORyVQw1Vy1wnNT29vs52WNfUgQ5MDPCFLyD7LWS9eiP-38Mg2KJyTO7qmouiwzcYs3vZZd-R0oYfvEQnw5J83CRoFOgXwYn_X93ruVeIRCKmPWKwtJOT92RYMgjRsjaB-bwcy6cF1VBEiiWlw1mm3E8N6A5LD15ShpyKvozIQfZDInugqgxIcJ7DCs0VJ3t4OmRyWOVvvZsqtHwfb0BTRj4n9druN7STt' alt='Rescue and recovery operations after migrant boats capsized near Al Khums' /><br /><h3>Highlights:</h3><ul><li>Boat breakdown: The Red Crescent said one vessel carried 26 people from Bangladesh and the other held 69 passengers including two Egyptians and many Sudanese, information provided in a Facebook statement.</li><li>Separate report: One outlet reported a separate sinking in the same area that may have left at least 42 people unaccounted for, a detail not covered by all sources.</li><li>Where it was posted: The Libyan Red Crescent published its account of the rescues on its verified Facebook page, according to coverage of its statement.</li><li>Geographic context: Al Khums sits on Libya’s coast about 118 km east of Tripoli, placing the incident along a commonly used central Mediterranean route.</li><li>Limited agency detail: News reports name the Red Crescent as a rescuer but do not specify other coastguard or naval involvement in these particular operations.</li></ul><h3>Sources:</h3><ul><li><a href='https://www.straitstimes.com/world/at-least-four-dead-as-two-migrant-boats-capsize-off-libyas-coast-red-crescent-says'>At least four dead as two migrant boats capsize off Libya’s coast, Red Crescent says</a> - straitstimes.com</li